00:05:43.036 --> 00:05:46.220
A few words about the
style of this class.

00:05:46.220 --> 00:05:50.760
We want to focus on
basic ideas and concepts.

00:05:50.760 --> 00:05:52.620
There's going to be
lots of formulas,

00:05:52.620 --> 00:05:54.710
but what we try to
do in this class

00:05:54.710 --> 00:05:56.530
is to actually
have you understand

00:05:56.530 --> 00:05:58.190
what those formulas mean.

00:05:58.190 --> 00:06:01.260
And, in a year from now when
almost all of the formulas

00:06:01.260 --> 00:06:03.510
have been wiped out
from your memory,

00:06:03.510 --> 00:06:05.610
you still have the
basic concepts.

00:06:05.610 --> 00:06:08.690
You can understand them, so
when you look things up again,

00:06:08.690 --> 00:06:12.820
they will still make sense.

00:06:12.820 --> 00:06:15.650
It's not the plug and
chug kind of class

00:06:15.650 --> 00:06:19.210
where you're given a list of
formulas, you're given numbers,

00:06:19.210 --> 00:06:21.470
and you plug in and
you get answers.

00:06:21.470 --> 00:06:24.950
The really hard part is
usually to choose which

00:06:24.950 --> 00:06:26.280
formulas you're going to use.

00:06:26.280 --> 00:06:28.900
You need judgment,
you need intuition.

00:06:28.900 --> 00:06:32.400
Lots of probability problems,
at least the interesting ones,

00:06:32.400 --> 00:06:34.450
often have lots of
different solutions.

00:06:34.450 --> 00:06:37.440
Some are extremely long,
some are extremely short.

00:06:37.440 --> 00:06:40.430
The extremely short ones
usually involve some kind

00:06:40.430 --> 00:06:43.860
of deeper understanding of
what's going on so that you

00:06:43.860 --> 00:06:46.350
can pick a shortcut and use it.

00:06:46.350 --> 00:06:49.110
And hopefully you are
going to develop this skill

00:06:49.110 --> 00:06:51.630
during this class.

00:06:51.630 --> 00:06:56.360
Now, I could spend a lot of
time in this lecture talking

00:06:56.360 --> 00:06:58.570
about why the
subject is important.

00:06:58.570 --> 00:07:02.270
I'll keep it short because
I think it's almost obvious.

00:07:02.270 --> 00:07:05.650
Anything that happens
in life is uncertain.

00:07:05.650 --> 00:07:08.910
There's uncertainty anywhere,
so whatever you try to do,

00:07:08.910 --> 00:07:11.830
you need to have some way
of dealing or thinking

00:07:11.830 --> 00:07:13.930
about this uncertainty.

00:07:13.930 --> 00:07:16.280
And the way to do that
in a systematic way

00:07:16.280 --> 00:07:17.955
is by using the
models that are given

00:07:17.955 --> 00:07:20.110
to us by probability theory.

00:07:20.110 --> 00:07:21.800
So if you're an
engineer and you're

00:07:21.800 --> 00:07:24.630
dealing with a communication
system or signal processing,

00:07:24.630 --> 00:07:28.440
basically you're facing
a fight against noise.

00:07:28.440 --> 00:07:30.380
Noise is random, is uncertain.

00:07:30.380 --> 00:07:31.450
How do you model it?

00:07:31.450 --> 00:07:33.120
How do you deal with it?

00:07:33.120 --> 00:07:35.210
If you're a manager,
I guess you're

00:07:35.210 --> 00:07:38.410
dealing with customer demand,
which is, of course, random.

00:07:38.410 --> 00:07:40.950
Or you're dealing
with the stock market,

00:07:40.950 --> 00:07:42.820
which is definitely random.

00:07:42.820 --> 00:07:48.190
Or you play the casino, which
is, again, random, and so on.

00:07:48.190 --> 00:07:50.800
And the same goes for
pretty much any other field

00:07:50.800 --> 00:07:52.880
that you can think of.

00:07:52.880 --> 00:07:57.190
But, independent of which
field you're coming from,

00:07:57.190 --> 00:08:00.630
the basic concepts and tools
are really all the same.

00:08:00.630 --> 00:08:03.100
So you may see in
